{"title_page": "A Just Russia", "text_new": "{{expand Russian|\u0421\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f|topic=gov|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = A Just Russia\n| native_name = \u0421\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f\n| logo = [[File:A Just Russia.svg|125px]]\n| colorcode = {{A Just Russia/meta/color}}\n| leader = [[Sergey Mironov]]\n| leader2_title = Parliamentary Leader\n| leader2_name = [[Sergey Mironov]]\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2006|10|28|df=y}}\n| merger = [[Left-wing]] of [[Rodina (political party)|Rodina]]<br />[[Russian Party of Life]]\n| headquarters = [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n| ideology = [[Democratic socialism]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/><br />[[Social democracy]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/><ref name=\"russia_analytical_digest_political_parties\"/>\n| position ={{nowrap|[[Centrism|Centre]]<ref>{{cite book|author1=Mark Kesselman|author2=Joel Krieger|author3=William A. Joseph|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=h0mGxhIzcBIC&pg=PA243&lpg=PA243&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Introduction to Comparative Politics: Brief Edition|page=243|publisher=[[Cengage Learning]]|date=18 March 2008|isbn=0-618-86683-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Ed Hancox|url=https://www.mic.com/articles/6510/anti-putin-protests-have-ended-but-grassroots-democracy-movement-growing-in-russia|title=Anti-Putin Protests Have Ended, But Grassroots Democracy Movement Growing in Russia|quote=First is the fact that Russia's typically fractious opposition parties were able to rally 'round Urlashov's candidacy: the Communists, the liberal Yabloko party and centrist A Just Russia all supported Urlashov.|work=[[Mic (media company)|Mic]]|date=6 April 2012}}</ref> to [[Centre-left politics|centre-left]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.rian.ru/russia/20111210/169537322.html|title=A Just Russia nominates pro-Kremlin Mironov for president|date=10 December 2011|publisher=|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldnews.about.com/od/russia/tp/Political-Parties-In-Russia.htm|title=Political Parties and Representation in Russia|author=Bridget Johnson|work=About.com News & Issues|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/a-just-russia-threatened-as-founding-groups-split-from-party/470624.html|title=A Just Russia Threatened as Founding Groups Split From Party - News|work=The Moscow Times|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref>}}\n| european = \n| international = {{nowrap|[[Socialist International]]<ref name=\"russia_analytical_digest_political_parties\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://socialistinternational.org/viewArticle.cfm?ArticlePageID=931|title=Socialist International - Progressive Politics For A Fairer World|website=socialistinternational.org|access-date=2012-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503204531/http://www.socialistinternational.org/viewArticle.cfm?ArticlePageID=931|archive-date=2013-05-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>}}\n| colours = {{color box|{{A Just Russia/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Orange (colour)|Orange]]<br>{{color box|#B40204|border=darkgray}} [[Red]]\n| seats1_title = [[Federation Council|Seats in the Federation Council]]\n| seats1 = {{composition bar|1|170|hex={{A Just Russia/meta/color}}}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spravedlivo.ru/1_69.html|title=\u0421\u041f\u0420\u0410\u0412\u0415\u0414\u041b\u0418\u0412\u0410\u042f \u0420\u041e\u0421\u0421\u0418\u042f|website=spravedlivo.ru}}</ref>\n| seats2_title = [[State Duma|Seats in the State Duma]]\n| seats2 = {{composition bar|22|450|hex={{A Just Russia/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[List of current heads of federal subjects of Russia|Governors]]\n| seats3 = {{composition bar|1|85|hex={{A Just Russia/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = [[Regional parliaments of Russia|Seats in the Regional Parliaments]]\n| seats4 = {{composition bar|187|3928|hex={{A Just Russia/meta/color}}}}\n| website = {{url|spravedlivo.ru}}\n| country = Russia\n}}\n'''A Just Russia'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialistinternational.org/viewArticle.cfm?ArticlePageID=931 |title=Progressive Politics For A Fairer World |publisher=Socialist International |date= |accessdate=2011-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://en.ria.ru/russia/20111210/169537322.html | title=A Just Russia nominates pro-Kremlin Mironov for president | work=[[RIA Novosti]] | date=10 December 2011 | accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref> ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f}}, '''\u0421\u0420''', ''Spravedlivaya Rossiya'', '''SR'''), also translated as '''Fair Russia'''<ref>{{citation| url= http://rt.com/politics/227763-russia-free-land-bill/ | title = Leftists propose free land for poor and distinguished Russians| date = 30 Jan 2015| work = rt.com }}</ref><ref>{{citation| url =http://www.kommersant.com/p717458/r_1/Fair_Russia_Party/| title =Sergei Mironov's New Party Holds First Convention, Suffers First Split| date =30 Oct 2006| work =www.kommersant.com| access-date =31 January 2015| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20150402111733/http://www.kommersant.com/p717458/r_1/Fair_Russia_Party/| archive-date =2 April 2015| url-status =dead| df =dmy-all}}</ref> or '''A Fair and Just Russia''',<ref>{{citation| url= http://www.sras.org/fair_and_just_russia | title = A FAIR AND JUST RUSSIA: RUSSIA'S SOCIAL DEMOCRATS | date = 3 June 2009| work = www.sras.org}}</ref> is a [[Social democracy|social-democratic]]<ref name=\"russia_analytical_digest_political_parties\"/><ref name=\"Nordsieck\">{{cite web|last=Nordsieck|first=Wolfram|title=Russia|website=Parties and Elections in Europe|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/russia.html|year=2016|accessdate=20 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Ilic2013\">{{cite book|author=Melanie Ilic|title=Life Stories of Soviet Women: The Interwar Generation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F2WMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA236|date=15 August 2013|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-135-09478-2|pages=236\u2013}}</ref> [[Political parties in Russia|political party in Russia]].\n\nThe party was formed on 28 October 2006 as a merger of the left-wing of [[Rodina (political party)|Rodina]], the [[Russian Party of Life]] and the [[Russian Pensioners' Party]]. Later, six further minor parties joined.<ref name=\"history\"/> <ref name=\"platform2\"/>           It calls for a \"[[Liberal socialism|New Socialism of the 21st Century]]\" which guarantees the rights and freedoms of the individual and ensures the proper functioning of a [[welfare state]].                                              In 2011, [[Nikolai Levichev]] was elected as party chairman, succeeding [[Sergey Mironov]] who led the party in 2006\u20132011. On 27 October 2013, Mironov was re-elected as party chairman.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nA Just Russia currently holds 23 of the 450 seats in the [[State Duma]]. It is widely considered to be a sub-party under [[United Russia]], the ruling political party of Russia, as it is one of the only few other parties that can currently participate in national-level elections in the Russian Federation.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== History ==\n=== Establishment ===\nA Just Russia formed on 28 October 2006 as a merger of three parties, namely [[Rodina (political party)|Rodina]], the [[Russian Party of Life]] and the [[Russian Party of Pensioners for Justice|Party of Pensioners]]. Of these, the nationalist Rodina was the largest, having won 9% of the popular vote in the [[2003 Russian legislative election|2003 Duma elections]]. At the time of the merger, Rodina had 37 seats in the Duma. The Party of Pensioners had gained 3% of the vote, failing to cross the 5% election threshold and also been weakened by infighting in its leadership. The [[social democracy|social-democratic]] Party of Life led by [[Sergey Mironov]] was still relatively young and had won only one regional election.<ref name=\"history\"/><ref name=\"mcfaul\"/>\n\nAs the only party of the three with seats in the Duma, Rodina dominated the unification process. In simultaneous conventions held in [[Moscow]] on 26 August 2006, the Party of Life and the Party of Pensioners decided to join Rodina.<ref name=\"platform1\"/> Two months later on 28 October 2006, the new party held its founding congress which decided to change the party's name to A Just Russia.<ref name=\"history\">[http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_foreword/ History] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005071657/http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_foreword/ |date=October 5, 2011 }} A Just Russia</ref> Mironov was elected the unified party's chairman while Rodina's former chairman [[Alexander Babakov]] became the secretary of the central council presidium and the leader of the Party of Pensioners [[Igor Zotov]] became secretary of the political council.<ref name=\"mcfaul\">{{cite book |last1= McFaul |first1= Michael |last2=Stoner-Weiss |first2=Kathryn |editor1-first= Stephen |editor1-last=White |title= Developments in Russian Politics 7|year= 2010 |publisher= Palgrave Macmillan |location= New York |isbn= 978-0-230-22449-0 |chapter= Elections and Voters}}</ref><ref name=\"platform1\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20180720225144/http://www.sras.org/fair_and_just_russia A Fair and Just Russia The Political Platform of Russia's Social Democrats Part 1: Philosophy and the Current State of Russia] The School of Russian and Asian Studies. Archived 20 July 2018.</ref> The next year, A Just Russia expanded further, absorbing three additional small parties in 2007, namely the [[People's Party of the Russian Federation|People's Party]],<ref>{{cite web|url= http://english.people.com.cn/200704/15/eng20070415_366565.html|title= People's Daily Online  -- Two Russian left-leaning parties unite|publisher= |accessdate= 16 March 2015}}</ref> the [[Party of Entrepreneurship Development]] and the [[Party of Constitutional Democrats]].<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\n[[File:Spravedlivaya.svg|thumb|Former logo of the party until 2011]]\nAt the party's founding convention, chairman Sergey Mironov expressed support for the direction given to the country by President [[Vladimir Putin]], claiming that \"we will not allow anyone to veer from it after Putin leaves his post in 2008\". At the same time, he harshly criticised Putin's party [[United Russia]] and what Mironov called the largest party's \"monopoly\" of the nation's political, economic and administrative resources.<ref name=\"sptimes_founding\"/> Mironov characterised A Just Russia as a new \"leftist political force\" and a \"hard opposition\",<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1072426.html|title= Russia: Parties Unite Into Nominal Opposition Force|work= RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|accessdate= 16 March 2015}}</ref> saying that \"if United Russia is the party of power, we will become the party of the people\".<ref name=\"sptimes_founding\">[http://www.sptimes.ru/index.php?action_id=100&story_id=19303 New 'Just Russia' Party Says Putin Knows Best] St Petersburg Times, 31 October 2006</ref> {{quote|The members of the political party ''Spravedlivaya Rossiya'' (A Just Russia) are people who have united in order to strengthen the Russian state in the interests of the people, and to create a just and equitable society in Russia. Such a society, which honours traditions, is proud of its history, and respects the elder generation, is constantly evolving and looks to the future with confidence.|From the party manifesto published in the founding congress of 28 August 2006<ref name=\"founding\">[http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_news/2.php CONGRESS IN MOSCOW] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005071854/http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_news/2.php |date=October 5, 2011 }} A Just Russia, 30 August 2006</ref>}}\n\nAccording to Professor [[Richard Sakwa]], the [[siloviki]] faction in the [[Presidential Administration of Russia|presidential administration]] supported the establishment of A Just Russia whose was to create a more [[Left-wing politics|left]]-oriented alternative to United Russia. [[Vladislav Surkov]], the leading force behind United Russia opposed the creation of the new party.<ref>Sakwa 2011, p.19</ref>\n\n=== First election successes ===\n[[File:Siergiej Mironow.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Sergey Mironov]] served as the party's chairman in 2006\u20132011 while also holding the position of the [[Federation Council]] chairman]]\nShortly after its creation, A Just Russia participated in its first elections when the party's candidate {{ill|Victor Alexandrovich Tarhov|ru|\u0422\u0430\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432, \u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}} won the mayoral race in [[Samara, Russia|Samara]]. The March 2007 regional elections were dominated by United Russia, but A Just Russia also put up a strong performance. In particular, the new party won a majority in the regional parliament in [[Stavropol Krai]].<ref name=\"Sakwa 2011, p.66\">Sakwa 2011, p.66</ref>\n\nThe emergence of A Just Russia changed Russia's political landscape and demonstrated that the country's leadership had been split between two parties. United Russia supporters in the presidential administration grew wary of the challenge posed by A Just Russia, worrying that United Russia would lose its position as \"the president's party\". Before the [[2007 Russian legislative election|2007 Duma elections]], the Kremlin had withdrawn its support of A Just Russia and threw its weight entirely behind United Russia.<ref name=\"Sakwa 2011, p.66\"/>\n\nIn a press conference on 19 January 2007 dedicated to upcoming Duma elections, Secretary of the Central Party Council of A Just Russia [[Alexander Babakov]] announced that the party had approximately 300,000 members.<ref name=\"jan2007_members\">[http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_news/12.php Alexander Babakov: The party numbers around 300,000] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005071736/http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_news/12.php |date=October 5, 2011 }} A Just Russia, 22 January 2007</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, A Just Russia's chairman [[Sergey Mironov]] proposed a merger between his party and the [[Communist Party of the Russian Federation]] in order to create a new unified [[socialism|socialist]] party.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=11579806&PageNum=0 |accessdate=February 19, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204162453/http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=11579806&PageNum=0 |archivedate=February 4, 2011 |title=ITAR-TASS |website=www.itar-tass.com}}</ref> Mironov invited all \"honest socialists\" to join the party. However, his proposal was rejected by [[Gennady Zyuganov]], leader of the Communists, who claimed that A Just Russia's claim to be a leftist party was \"a charade\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.rian.ru/russia/20070529/66284043.html |title=Communists refuse to unite with Just Russia &#124; Russia &#124; RIA Novosti |publisher=En.rian.ru |date=2007-05-29 |accessdate=2011-12-06}}</ref>\n\n=== 2007 Duma elections ===\n[[File:Election russia 2007 007.jpg|thumb|A Just Russia election poster in [[Saint Petersburg]] in November 2007, one month before the [[2007 Russian legislative election|Duma elections]] in which the party received 16% of the votes from the city]]\nIn the run-up to the December [[2007 Russian legislative election|2007 Duma elections]], President [[Vladimir Putin]]\u2014the country's most popular politician\u2014explicitly and unequivocally endorsed the [[United Russia]] party and decided to head its national list. Putin's decision significantly changed the election campaign and resulted in a massive boost to United Russia's popularity. This represented a harsh blow to A Just Russia which also had hoped to ride on Putin's popularity.<ref>Sakwa 2011, p.220-221</ref> Polls suggested the party could have difficulties crossing the 7% election threshold.<ref name=\"sakwa_p248\">Sakwa 2011, p.248</ref>\n\nA Just Russia appointed three persons to its national list, namely chairman [[Sergey Mironov]]; [[Svetlana Goryacheva]] (a former member of the [[Communist Party of the Russian Federation]]); and {{illm|Sergey Shargunov|de|Sergei Alexandrowitsch Schargunow|ru|\u0428\u0430\u0440\u0433\u0443\u043d\u043e\u0432, \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}}, a 27-year-old fiction author.<ref>Sakwa 2011, p.222</ref> In its regional lists, A Just Russia had 553 candidates, taking its total number of candidates to 556. This was more than the Communists (515), but less than United Russia (600).<ref>Sakwa 2011, p.228</ref> Although originally positioned as a [[centre-left]] party, under Mironov's leadership A Just Russia campaigned as a socialist alternative to the Communists.<ref name=\"sakwa_p248\"/>\n\nIn the end, A Just Russia received 5,383,639 votes (7.74%), becoming the fourth party to cross the 7% election threshold and enter the Duma after United Russia, the Communists and the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia]]. As a result, A Just Russia got 38 of the 450 seats (8.4%) in the Duma.<ref name=\"results2007\">[http://www.russiavotes.org/duma/duma_today.php FINAL RESULT OF THE DUMA ELECTION, 2 DECEMBER 2007] Levada Center</ref> The party received its highest share of votes in [[Astrakhan]] (20%), [[Saint Petersburg]] (16%) and [[Stavropol]] (13%). In Saint Petersburg, the hometown of chairman Mironov, A Just Russia became the second largest party. Mironov said he would not take up his seat in the Duma himself, but instead continue as the Chairman of the [[Federation Council]].<ref name=\"sakwa_p248\"/><ref>[http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/international/party_english/english_articles/41.php Sergey Mironov summarizes the Results of the Elections] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005071831/http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/international/party_english/english_articles/41.php |date=October 5, 2011 }} A Just Russia, 13 December 2007</ref> A Just Russia's performance in the elections was a slight disappointment, especially since one of its predecessor parties, [[Rodina (political party)|Rodina]], had won 9% of the votes in the [[2003 Russian legislative election|2003 elections]].<ref name=\"sakwa_p248\"/>\n\n=== Post-election ===\nOn 10 December 2007, A Just Russia was part of a coalition of parties which nominated [[Dmitry Medvedev]] as their candidate for the [[2008 Russian presidential election|2008 presidential elections]].<ref name=\"lenta20071210\">{{cite news|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2007/12/10/medvedev/|script-title=ru:\u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041c\u0435\u0434\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0432 \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0442 \u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|publisher=[[Lenta.Ru]]|language=Russian|date=10 December 2007|accessdate=30 November 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081225054718/http://lenta.ru/news/2007/12/10/medvedev/| archivedate= 25 December 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 April 2008, A Just Russia held its third annual congress, where the party expelled thousands of members who were not aware that they were members. The party's charter was amended at the congress to make mergers easier. The congress also disbanded the party's [[politburo]] and transferred its functions to the Central Council. Politburo's chairman [[Nikolai Levichev]], who also heads A Just Russia's faction in the [[State Duma]], was elected as the council's first secretary.\n\nDuring its XXIII Congress On 30 June 2008, A Just Russia was accepted into the [[Socialist International]], the worldwide organisation of social-democratic political parties.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\nThe [[United Socialist Party of Russia]] and the [[Russian Ecological Party \"The Greens\"]] merged into the party in 2008. This means that the total of parties that have merged into A Just Russia is nine.<ref name=\"history\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Sras.Org |url=http://www.sras.org/fair_and_just_russia |title=A Fair and Just Russia: Russia's Social Democrats |publisher=Sras.org |date= |accessdate=2011-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Oleg Rt. |url=http://greenparty.ru/news_id.php?id=2009062616445229 |title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044f \"\u0417\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u044b\u0435\" |publisher=Greenparty.ru |accessdate=2011-12-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007232020/http://greenparty.ru/news_id.php?id=2009062616445229 |archivedate=2011-10-07 }}</ref>\n\nIn the 2007\u20132011 State Duma, A Just Russia became a strong supporter of the [[Medvedev modernisation programme]], endorsing President [[Dmitry Medvedev]]'s view that Russia must move towards a diversified [[post-industrial economy]] and democratisation of its political system. A Just Russia also advocated restoration of direct gubernatorial elections and lowering the Duma election threshold from 7% to 3%. A Just Russia voted against Prime Minister [[Vladimir Putin]]'s anti-crisis plan in April 2009 and also voted against the governments budgets in 2010 and 2011. According to researcher Luke March, in the [[5th State Duma|2007\u20132011 Duma]] A Just Russia clearly moved towards Medvedev. The party has declared absolute opposition to Putin's government while remaining supportive of Medvedev.<ref name=\"russia_analytical_digest_political_parties\">{{cite journal |first=Luke |last=March |title=Just Russia\u2014From \"Second Leg\" to \"Footnote\"? |journal=Russian Analytical Digest |issue=102 |pages=7\u201310 |date=26 September 2011 |url=http://www.isn.ethz.ch/isn/Digital-Library/Publications/Detail/?ots591=0c54e3b3-1e9c-be1e-2c24-a6a8c7060233&lng=en&id=133117 |accessdate=13 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nA Just Russia announced that they would not run in the [[2018 Russian presidential election|2018 presidential election]] and instead would support President Putin for the elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rbc.ru/politics/25/12/2017/5a40bc719a79470d6296e296?from=newsfeed|title=\u041c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043b \u043d\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0432 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \"\u043b\u0438\u0431\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043b\u044e\u0434\u043e\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\"|website=\u0420\u0411\u041a|access-date=2017-12-25}}</ref>\n\n== Current status ==\nA Just Russia has 23 representatives in the 450-seat [[State Duma]]. The party holds two committee chairmanships, the Committee on Family, Women and Children Affairs (headed by [[Yelena Mizulina]]) and the Committee on Science and High Technologies (headed by [[Valeriy Chereshnev]]). In the upper house, the [[Federation Council]], the party has 12 members, representing the interests of different regions. On the sub-national level, the party has a total of 309 deputies in 66 regional assemblies.<ref name=\"about\">[http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_foreword/ ABOUT US] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005071657/http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_foreword/ |date=October 5, 2011 }} A Just Russia</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the party had 400,000 members and claimed to be the largest [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] party in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spravedlivo.ru/international/party_english/english_foreword/ |title=English - About us - \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0421\u041f\u0420\u0410\u0412\u0415\u0414\u041b\u0418\u0412\u0410\u042f \u0420\u041e\u0421\u0421\u0418\u042f |accessdate=2012-11-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106075215/http://www.spravedlivo.ru/international/party_english/english_foreword |archivedate=2012-01-06 }}</ref> It has regional branches in all [[federal subjects of Russia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minjust.ru/ru/activity/nko/partii/SR/|title=\u0414\u0435\u044f\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c|publisher=|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Platform ==\nA Just Russia calls for a [[welfare state]] with less [[economic inequality]], but protecting individual [[private property#Socialist perspective|property rights]] and maintaining a [[market socialism|market economy]]. Under [[Sergey Mironov]], the party has presented itself as a socialist alternative to the [[Communist Party of the Russian Federation]]<ref name=\"sakwa_p248\"/> and describes its ideology as \"New Socialism of the 21st century\", but emphasises that it does not wish to return to \"Soviet bureaucratic socialism\".{{citation needed|date=October 2018}} In the party platform, this \"New Socialism\" is defined as the antithesis of \"barbarous, oligarchic capitalism\". It represents a more [[individualism|individualist]] or [[liberal socialism]].<ref name=\"platform2\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20180727212226/http://www.sras.org/fair_and_just_russia_2 A Fair and Just Russia. The Political Platform of Russia's Social Democrats Part 2: The Individual & Government] The School of Russian and Asian Studies. Archived 27 July 2018.</ref><ref name=\"platform1\"/>\n\nImproving the socio-economic position of the average Russian is the party's primary aim. It wishes to replace Russia's 13% [[flat tax|flat income tax]] with [[progressive taxation]] and demands that spending on employment programmes is increased to 1% of GDP.<ref name=\"platform2\"/><ref name=\"platform1\"/> In the State Duma, the party emphasises its role as \"constructive opposition\" that opposes high-level corruption and supports further democratisation of the political system. In the [[5th State Duma|2007\u20132011 Duma]], A Just Russia declared absolute opposition to Prime Minister [[Vladimir Putin]]'s government, voting against the government's budgets in 2010 and 2011 while remaining strongly supportive of President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and his [[Medvedev modernisation programme|modernisation programme]].<ref name=\"russia_analytical_digest_political_parties\"/>\n\n== Chairmen ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!\u2116\n!Portrait\n!Chairmen\n!Took office\n!Left office\n|-\n!1\n|[[File:S M Mironov.jpg|90x90px|center]]\n|[[Sergey Mironov]]\n|28 October 2006\n|16 April 2011\n|-\n!2\n|[[File:Nikolay Levichev IF 09-2013 (1).jpg|90x90px|center]]\n|[[Nikolai Levichev]]\n|16 April 2011\n|27 October 2013\n|-\n!3\n|[[File:Sergey Mironov 2014-05-01 1.jpg|90x90px|center]]\n|[[Sergey Mironov]]\n|27 October 2013\n|Incumbent\n|}\n\n== International cooperation ==\nA Just Russia is a full member of the [[Socialist International]].\n\n== Electoral results ==\n=== Presidential elections ===\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Election year\n!rowspan=2|Candidate\n!colspan=2|1st round\n!colspan=2|2nd round\n|-\n!No. of overall votes\n!% of overall vote\n!No. of overall votes\n!% of overall vote\n|-\n![[2008 Russian presidential election|2008]]\n|colspan=3|Supported [[Dmitry Medvedev]]\n|colspan=2 bgcolor=lightgrey|\n|-\n![[2012 Russian presidential election|2012]]\n|[[Sergey Mironov]]\n|2,755,642\n|3.9 (5th)\n|colspan=2 bgcolor=lightgrey|\n|-\n![[2018 Russian presidential election|2018]]\n|colspan=3|Supported [[Vladimir Putin]]\n|colspan=2 bgcolor=lightgrey|\n|}\n\n=== Legislative elections ===\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!Election year\n!No. of overall votes\n!% of overall vote\n!No. of seats won\n!+/-\n!Leader\n|-\n![[2007 Russian legislative election|2007]]\n|5,383,639\n|7.4 (4th)\n|{{composition bar|38|450|hex={{A Just Russia/meta/color}}}}\n|{{nochange}}\n|[[Sergey Mironov]]\n|-\n![[2011 Russian legislative election|2011]]\n|8,695,522\n|13.2 (3rd)\n|{{composition bar|64|450|hex={{A Just Russia/meta/color}}}}\n|{{increase}} 26\n|[[Nikolai Levichev]]\n|-\n![[2016 Russian legislative election|2016]]\n|3,242,284\n|6.2 (4th)\n|{{composition bar|23|450|hex={{A Just Russia/meta/color}}}}\n|{{decrease}} 41\n|[[Sergey Mironov]]\n|}\n\n== Mergers ==\n* [[People's Party of the Russian Federation]] (2000\u20132007)\n* [[Russian Party of Life]] (2002\u20132006)\n* [[Party of Social Justice]] (2002\u20132008)\n* [[United Socialist Party of Russia]] (2003\u20132008)\n* [[Rodina (political party)|Rodina]] (2006\u20132012)\n* [[Party of Growth]] (2006\u20132012)\n* [[Russian Party of Pensioners for Social Justice|Pensioners Party]] (2006\u20132012)\n* [[Russian Ecological Party \"The Greens\"|The Greens]] (2006\u20132012)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Literature ==\n* {{cite book|title=The Crisis of Russian Democracy: Dual State, Factionalism and the Medvedev Succession|last=Sakwa|first=Richard|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-14522-0|year=2011}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://spravedlivo.ru/}} {{in lang|ru}}\n* [http://sp-ros.ru/ Website of Moscow oblast regional committee] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [http://www.wsis-community.org/pg/blog/read/2967089/project-international-day-of-peace-via-art A Just Russia prepares the International day of the UN] on the website of the [[World Summit on the Information Society|WSIS]] {{in lang|ru|en}}\n\n{{Russian political parties}}\n{{Socialist parties in the Russian Federation}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Just Russia}}\n[[Category:A Just Russia| ]]\n[[Category:Registered political parties in Russia]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2006]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Russia]]\n[[Category:Centrist parties in Russia]]\n[[Category:Social democratic parties in Russia]]\n[[Category:Socialist International]]\n[[Category:Democratic socialist parties in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{expand Russian|\u0421\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f|topic=gov|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = A Just Russia\n| native_name = \u0421\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f\n| logo = [[File:A Just Russia.svg|125px]]\n| colorcode = {{A Just Russia/meta/color}}\n| leader = [[Sergey Mironov]]\n| leader2_title = Parliamentary Leader\n| leader2_name = [[Sergey Mironov]]\n| foundation = {{start date and age|2006|10|28|df=y}}\n| merger = [[Left-wing]] of [[Rodina (political party)|Rodina]]<br />[[Russian Party of Life]]\n| headquarters = [[Moscow]], [[Russia]]\n| ideology = [[Democratic socialism]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/><br />[[Social democracy]]<ref name=\"Nordsieck\"/><ref name=\"russia_analytical_digest_political_parties\"/>\n| position ={{nowrap|[[Centrism|Centre]]<ref>{{cite book|author1=Mark Kesselman|author2=Joel Krieger|author3=William A. Joseph|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=h0mGxhIzcBIC&pg=PA243&lpg=PA243&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Introduction to Comparative Politics: Brief Edition|page=243|publisher=[[Cengage Learning]]|date=18 March 2008|isbn=0-618-86683-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Ed Hancox|url=https://www.mic.com/articles/6510/anti-putin-protests-have-ended-but-grassroots-democracy-movement-growing-in-russia|title=Anti-Putin Protests Have Ended, But Grassroots Democracy Movement Growing in Russia|quote=First is the fact that Russia's typically fractious opposition parties were able to rally 'round Urlashov's candidacy: the Communists, the liberal Yabloko party and centrist A Just Russia all supported Urlashov.|work=[[Mic (media company)|Mic]]|date=6 April 2012}}</ref> to [[Centre-left politics|centre-left]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.rian.ru/russia/20111210/169537322.html|title=A Just Russia nominates pro-Kremlin Mironov for president|date=10 December 2011|publisher=|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldnews.about.com/od/russia/tp/Political-Parties-In-Russia.htm|title=Political Parties and Representation in Russia|author=Bridget Johnson|work=About.com News & Issues|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/a-just-russia-threatened-as-founding-groups-split-from-party/470624.html|title=A Just Russia Threatened as Founding Groups Split From Party - News|work=The Moscow Times|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref>}}\n| european = \n| international = {{nowrap|[[Socialist International]]<ref name=\"russia_analytical_digest_political_parties\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://socialistinternational.org/viewArticle.cfm?ArticlePageID=931|title=Socialist International - Progressive Politics For A Fairer World|website=socialistinternational.org|access-date=2012-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503204531/http://www.socialistinternational.org/viewArticle.cfm?ArticlePageID=931|archive-date=2013-05-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>}}\n| colours = {{color box|{{A Just Russia/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Orange (colour)|Orange]] {{color box|#B40204|border=darkgray}} [[Red]]\n| seats1_title = [[Federation Council|Seats in the Federation Council]]\n| seats1 = {{composition bar|1|170|hex={{A Just Russia/meta/color}}}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spravedlivo.ru/1_69.html|title=\u0421\u041f\u0420\u0410\u0412\u0415\u0414\u041b\u0418\u0412\u0410\u042f \u0420\u041e\u0421\u0421\u0418\u042f|website=spravedlivo.ru}}</ref>\n| seats2_title = [[State Duma|Seats in the State Duma]]\n| seats2 = {{composition bar|22|450|hex={{A Just Russia/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = [[List of current heads of federal subjects of Russia|Governors]]\n| seats3 = {{composition bar|1|85|hex={{A Just Russia/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = [[Regional parliaments of Russia|Seats in the Regional Parliaments]]\n| seats4 = {{composition bar|187|3928|hex={{A Just Russia/meta/color}}}}\n| website = {{url|spravedlivo.ru}}\n| country = Russia\n}}\n'''A Just Russia'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.socialistinternational.org/viewArticle.cfm?ArticlePageID=931 |title=Progressive Politics For A Fairer World |publisher=Socialist International |date= |accessdate=2011-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://en.ria.ru/russia/20111210/169537322.html | title=A Just Russia nominates pro-Kremlin Mironov for president | work=[[RIA Novosti]] | date=10 December 2011 | accessdate=17 January 2012}}</ref> ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0434\u043b\u0438\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044f}}, '''\u0421\u0420''', ''Spravedlivaya Rossiya'', '''SR'''), also translated as '''Fair Russia'''<ref>{{citation| url= http://rt.com/politics/227763-russia-free-land-bill/ | title = Leftists propose free land for poor and distinguished Russians| date = 30 Jan 2015| work = rt.com }}</ref><ref>{{citation| url =http://www.kommersant.com/p717458/r_1/Fair_Russia_Party/| title =Sergei Mironov's New Party Holds First Convention, Suffers First Split| date =30 Oct 2006| work =www.kommersant.com| access-date =31 January 2015| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20150402111733/http://www.kommersant.com/p717458/r_1/Fair_Russia_Party/| archive-date =2 April 2015| url-status =dead| df =dmy-all}}</ref> or '''A Fair and Just Russia''',<ref>{{citation| url= http://www.sras.org/fair_and_just_russia | title = A FAIR AND JUST RUSSIA: RUSSIA'S SOCIAL DEMOCRATS | date = 3 June 2009| work = www.sras.org}}</ref> is a [[Social democracy|social-democratic]]<ref name=\"russia_analytical_digest_political_parties\"/><ref name=\"Nordsieck\">{{cite web|last=Nordsieck|first=Wolfram|title=Russia|website=Parties and Elections in Europe|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/russia.html|year=2016|accessdate=20 August 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Ilic2013\">{{cite book|author=Melanie Ilic|title=Life Stories of Soviet Women: The Interwar Generation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F2WMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA236|date=15 August 2013|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-135-09478-2|pages=236\u2013}}</ref> [[Political parties in Russia|political party in Russia]].\n\nThe party was formed on 28 October 2006 as a merger of the left-wing of [[Rodina (political party)|Rodina]], the [[Russian Party of Life]] and the [[Russian Pensioners' Party]]. Later, six further minor parties joined.<ref name=\"history\"/> <ref name=\"platform2\"/>           It calls for a \"[[Liberal socialism|New Socialism of the 21st Century]]\" which guarantees the rights and freedoms of the individual and ensures the proper functioning of a [[welfare state]].                                              In 2011, [[Nikolai Levichev]] was elected as party chairman, succeeding [[Sergey Mironov]] who led the party in 2006\u20132011. On 27 October 2013, Mironov was re-elected as party chairman.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nA Just Russia currently holds 23 of the 450 seats in the [[State Duma]]. It is widely considered to be a sub-party under [[United Russia]], the ruling political party of Russia, as it is one of the only few other parties that can currently participate in national-level elections in the Russian Federation.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== History ==\n=== Establishment ===\nA Just Russia formed on 28 October 2006 as a merger of three parties, namely [[Rodina (political party)|Rodina]], the [[Russian Party of Life]] and the [[Russian Party of Pensioners for Justice|Party of Pensioners]]. Of these, the nationalist Rodina was the largest, having won 9% of the popular vote in the [[2003 Russian legislative election|2003 Duma elections]]. At the time of the merger, Rodina had 37 seats in the Duma. The Party of Pensioners had gained 3% of the vote, failing to cross the 5% election threshold and also been weakened by infighting in its leadership. The [[social democracy|social-democratic]] Party of Life led by [[Sergey Mironov]] was still relatively young and had won only one regional election.<ref name=\"history\"/><ref name=\"mcfaul\"/>\n\nAs the only party of the three with seats in the Duma, Rodina dominated the unification process. In simultaneous conventions held in [[Moscow]] on 26 August 2006, the Party of Life and the Party of Pensioners decided to join Rodina.<ref name=\"platform1\"/> Two months later on 28 October 2006, the new party held its founding congress which decided to change the party's name to A Just Russia.<ref name=\"history\">[http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_foreword/ History] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005071657/http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_foreword/ |date=October 5, 2011 }} A Just Russia</ref> Mironov was elected the unified party's chairman while Rodina's former chairman [[Alexander Babakov]] became the secretary of the central council presidium and the leader of the Party of Pensioners [[Igor Zotov]] became secretary of the political council.<ref name=\"mcfaul\">{{cite book |last1= McFaul |first1= Michael |last2=Stoner-Weiss |first2=Kathryn |editor1-first= Stephen |editor1-last=White |title= Developments in Russian Politics 7|year= 2010 |publisher= Palgrave Macmillan |location= New York |isbn= 978-0-230-22449-0 |chapter= Elections and Voters}}</ref><ref name=\"platform1\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20180720225144/http://www.sras.org/fair_and_just_russia A Fair and Just Russia The Political Platform of Russia's Social Democrats Part 1: Philosophy and the Current State of Russia] The School of Russian and Asian Studies. Archived 20 July 2018.</ref> The next year, A Just Russia expanded further, absorbing three additional small parties in 2007, namely the [[People's Party of the Russian Federation|People's Party]],<ref>{{cite web|url= http://english.people.com.cn/200704/15/eng20070415_366565.html|title= People's Daily Online  -- Two Russian left-leaning parties unite|publisher= |accessdate= 16 March 2015}}</ref> the [[Party of Entrepreneurship Development]] and the [[Party of Constitutional Democrats]].<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\n[[File:Spravedlivaya.svg|thumb|Former logo of the party until 2011]]\nAt the party's founding convention, chairman Sergey Mironov expressed support for the direction given to the country by President [[Vladimir Putin]], claiming that \"we will not allow anyone to veer from it after Putin leaves his post in 2008\". At the same time, he harshly criticised Putin's party [[United Russia]] and what Mironov called the largest party's \"monopoly\" of the nation's political, economic and administrative resources.<ref name=\"sptimes_founding\"/> Mironov characterised A Just Russia as a new \"leftist political force\" and a \"hard opposition\",<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1072426.html|title= Russia: Parties Unite Into Nominal Opposition Force|work= RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|accessdate= 16 March 2015}}</ref> saying that \"if United Russia is the party of power, we will become the party of the people\".<ref name=\"sptimes_founding\">[http://www.sptimes.ru/index.php?action_id=100&story_id=19303 New 'Just Russia' Party Says Putin Knows Best] St Petersburg Times, 31 October 2006</ref> {{quote|The members of the political party ''Spravedlivaya Rossiya'' (A Just Russia) are people who have united in order to strengthen the Russian state in the interests of the people, and to create a just and equitable society in Russia. Such a society, which honours traditions, is proud of its history, and respects the elder generation, is constantly evolving and looks to the future with confidence.|From the party manifesto published in the founding congress of 28 August 2006<ref name=\"founding\">[http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_news/2.php CONGRESS IN MOSCOW] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005071854/http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_news/2.php |date=October 5, 2011 }} A Just Russia, 30 August 2006</ref>}}\n\nAccording to Professor [[Richard Sakwa]], the [[siloviki]] faction in the [[Presidential Administration of Russia|presidential administration]] supported the establishment of A Just Russia whose was to create a more [[Left-wing politics|left]]-oriented alternative to United Russia. [[Vladislav Surkov]], the leading force behind United Russia opposed the creation of the new party.<ref>Sakwa 2011, p.19</ref>\n\n=== First election successes ===\n[[File:Siergiej Mironow.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Sergey Mironov]] served as the party's chairman in 2006\u20132011 while also holding the position of the [[Federation Council]] chairman]]\nShortly after its creation, A Just Russia participated in its first elections when the party's candidate {{ill|Victor Alexandrovich Tarhov|ru|\u0422\u0430\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432, \u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}} won the mayoral race in [[Samara, Russia|Samara]]. The March 2007 regional elections were dominated by United Russia, but A Just Russia also put up a strong performance. In particular, the new party won a majority in the regional parliament in [[Stavropol Krai]].<ref name=\"Sakwa 2011, p.66\">Sakwa 2011, p.66</ref>\n\nThe emergence of A Just Russia changed Russia's political landscape and demonstrated that the country's leadership had been split between two parties. United Russia supporters in the presidential administration grew wary of the challenge posed by A Just Russia, worrying that United Russia would lose its position as \"the president's party\". Before the [[2007 Russian legislative election|2007 Duma elections]], the Kremlin had withdrawn its support of A Just Russia and threw its weight entirely behind United Russia.<ref name=\"Sakwa 2011, p.66\"/>\n\nIn a press conference on 19 January 2007 dedicated to upcoming Duma elections, Secretary of the Central Party Council of A Just Russia [[Alexander Babakov]] announced that the party had approximately 300,000 members.<ref name=\"jan2007_members\">[http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_news/12.php Alexander Babakov: The party numbers around 300,000] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005071736/http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_news/12.php |date=October 5, 2011 }} A Just Russia, 22 January 2007</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, A Just Russia's chairman [[Sergey Mironov]] proposed a merger between his party and the [[Communist Party of the Russian Federation]] in order to create a new unified [[socialism|socialist]] party.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=11579806&PageNum=0 |accessdate=February 19, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204162453/http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=11579806&PageNum=0 |archivedate=February 4, 2011 |title=ITAR-TASS |website=www.itar-tass.com}}</ref> Mironov invited all \"honest socialists\" to join the party. However, his proposal was rejected by [[Gennady Zyuganov]], leader of the Communists, who claimed that A Just Russia's claim to be a leftist party was \"a charade\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.rian.ru/russia/20070529/66284043.html |title=Communists refuse to unite with Just Russia &#124; Russia &#124; RIA Novosti |publisher=En.rian.ru |date=2007-05-29 |accessdate=2011-12-06}}</ref>\n\n=== 2007 Duma elections ===\n[[File:Election russia 2007 007.jpg|thumb|A Just Russia election poster in [[Saint Petersburg]] in November 2007, one month before the [[2007 Russian legislative election|Duma elections]] in which the party received 16% of the votes from the city]]\nIn the run-up to the December [[2007 Russian legislative election|2007 Duma elections]], President [[Vladimir Putin]]\u2014the country's most popular politician\u2014explicitly and unequivocally endorsed the [[United Russia]] party and decided to head its national list. Putin's decision significantly changed the election campaign and resulted in a massive boost to United Russia's popularity. This represented a harsh blow to A Just Russia which also had hoped to ride on Putin's popularity.<ref>Sakwa 2011, p.220-221</ref> Polls suggested the party could have difficulties crossing the 7% election threshold.<ref name=\"sakwa_p248\">Sakwa 2011, p.248</ref>\n\nA Just Russia appointed three persons to its national list, namely chairman [[Sergey Mironov]]; [[Svetlana Goryacheva]] (a former member of the [[Communist Party of the Russian Federation]]); and {{illm|Sergey Shargunov|de|Sergei Alexandrowitsch Schargunow|ru|\u0428\u0430\u0440\u0433\u0443\u043d\u043e\u0432, \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}}, a 27-year-old fiction author.<ref>Sakwa 2011, p.222</ref> In its regional lists, A Just Russia had 553 candidates, taking its total number of candidates to 556. This was more than the Communists (515), but less than United Russia (600).<ref>Sakwa 2011, p.228</ref> Although originally positioned as a [[centre-left]] party, under Mironov's leadership A Just Russia campaigned as a socialist alternative to the Communists.<ref name=\"sakwa_p248\"/>\n\nIn the end, A Just Russia received 5,383,639 votes (7.74%), becoming the fourth party to cross the 7% election threshold and enter the Duma after United Russia, the Communists and the [[Liberal Democratic Party of Russia]]. As a result, A Just Russia got 38 of the 450 seats (8.4%) in the Duma.<ref name=\"results2007\">[http://www.russiavotes.org/duma/duma_today.php FINAL RESULT OF THE DUMA ELECTION, 2 DECEMBER 2007] Levada Center</ref> The party received its highest share of votes in [[Astrakhan]] (20%), [[Saint Petersburg]] (16%) and [[Stavropol]] (13%). In Saint Petersburg, the hometown of chairman Mironov, A Just Russia became the second largest party. Mironov said he would not take up his seat in the Duma himself, but instead continue as the Chairman of the [[Federation Council]].<ref name=\"sakwa_p248\"/><ref>[http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/international/party_english/english_articles/41.php Sergey Mironov summarizes the Results of the Elections] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005071831/http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/international/party_english/english_articles/41.php |date=October 5, 2011 }} A Just Russia, 13 December 2007</ref> A Just Russia's performance in the elections was a slight disappointment, especially since one of its predecessor parties, [[Rodina (political party)|Rodina]], had won 9% of the votes in the [[2003 Russian legislative election|2003 elections]].<ref name=\"sakwa_p248\"/>\n\n=== Post-election ===\nOn 10 December 2007, A Just Russia was part of a coalition of parties which nominated [[Dmitry Medvedev]] as their candidate for the [[2008 Russian presidential election|2008 presidential elections]].<ref name=\"lenta20071210\">{{cite news|url=http://lenta.ru/news/2007/12/10/medvedev/|script-title=ru:\u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041c\u0435\u0434\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0432 \u0432\u044b\u0434\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0442 \u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|publisher=[[Lenta.Ru]]|language=Russian|date=10 December 2007|accessdate=30 November 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081225054718/http://lenta.ru/news/2007/12/10/medvedev/| archivedate= 25 December 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 April 2008, A Just Russia held its third annual congress, where the party expelled thousands of members who were not aware that they were members. The party's charter was amended at the congress to make mergers easier. The congress also disbanded the party's [[politburo]] and transferred its functions to the Central Council. Politburo's chairman [[Nikolai Levichev]], who also heads A Just Russia's faction in the [[State Duma]], was elected as the council's first secretary.\n\nDuring its XXIII Congress On 30 June 2008, A Just Russia was accepted into the [[Socialist International]], the worldwide organisation of social-democratic political parties.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\nThe [[United Socialist Party of Russia]] and the [[Russian Ecological Party \"The Greens\"]] merged into the party in 2008. This means that the total of parties that have merged into A Just Russia is nine.<ref name=\"history\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Sras.Org |url=http://www.sras.org/fair_and_just_russia |title=A Fair and Just Russia: Russia's Social Democrats |publisher=Sras.org |date= |accessdate=2011-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Oleg Rt. |url=http://greenparty.ru/news_id.php?id=2009062616445229 |title=\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044f \"\u0417\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u044b\u0435\" |publisher=Greenparty.ru |accessdate=2011-12-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007232020/http://greenparty.ru/news_id.php?id=2009062616445229 |archivedate=2011-10-07 }}</ref>\n\nIn the 2007\u20132011 State Duma, A Just Russia became a strong supporter of the [[Medvedev modernisation programme]], endorsing President [[Dmitry Medvedev]]'s view that Russia must move towards a diversified [[post-industrial economy]] and democratisation of its political system. A Just Russia also advocated restoration of direct gubernatorial elections and lowering the Duma election threshold from 7% to 3%. A Just Russia voted against Prime Minister [[Vladimir Putin]]'s anti-crisis plan in April 2009 and also voted against the governments budgets in 2010 and 2011. According to researcher Luke March, in the [[5th State Duma|2007\u20132011 Duma]] A Just Russia clearly moved towards Medvedev. The party has declared absolute opposition to Putin's government while remaining supportive of Medvedev.<ref name=\"russia_analytical_digest_political_parties\">{{cite journal |first=Luke |last=March |title=Just Russia\u2014From \"Second Leg\" to \"Footnote\"? |journal=Russian Analytical Digest |issue=102 |pages=7\u201310 |date=26 September 2011 |url=http://www.isn.ethz.ch/isn/Digital-Library/Publications/Detail/?ots591=0c54e3b3-1e9c-be1e-2c24-a6a8c7060233&lng=en&id=133117 |accessdate=13 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nA Just Russia announced that they would not run in the [[2018 Russian presidential election|2018 presidential election]] and instead would support President Putin for the elections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rbc.ru/politics/25/12/2017/5a40bc719a79470d6296e296?from=newsfeed|title=\u041c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043b \u043d\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u043f\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0432 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \"\u043b\u0438\u0431\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043b\u044e\u0434\u043e\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\"|website=\u0420\u0411\u041a|access-date=2017-12-25}}</ref>\n\n== Current status ==\nA Just Russia has 23 representatives in the 450-seat [[State Duma]]. The party holds two committee chairmanships, the Committee on Family, Women and Children Affairs (headed by [[Yelena Mizulina]]) and the Committee on Science and High Technologies (headed by [[Valeriy Chereshnev]]). In the upper house, the [[Federation Council]], the party has 12 members, representing the interests of different regions. On the sub-national level, the party has a total of 309 deputies in 66 regional assemblies.<ref name=\"about\">[http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_foreword/ ABOUT US] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005071657/http://www.spravedlivo.ru/information/party_english/english_foreword/ |date=October 5, 2011 }} A Just Russia</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the party had 400,000 members and claimed to be the largest [[Left-wing politics|left-wing]] party in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spravedlivo.ru/international/party_english/english_foreword/ |title=English - About us - \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044f \u0421\u041f\u0420\u0410\u0412\u0415\u0414\u041b\u0418\u0412\u0410\u042f \u0420\u041e\u0421\u0421\u0418\u042f |accessdate=2012-11-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106075215/http://www.spravedlivo.ru/international/party_english/english_foreword |archivedate=2012-01-06 }}</ref> It has regional branches in all [[federal subjects of Russia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minjust.ru/ru/activity/nko/partii/SR/|title=\u0414\u0435\u044f\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c|publisher=|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Platform ==\nA Just Russia calls for a [[welfare state]] with less [[economic inequality]], but protecting individual [[private property#Socialist perspective|property rights]] and maintaining a [[market socialism|market economy]]. Under [[Sergey Mironov]], the party has presented itself as a socialist alternative to the [[Communist Party of the Russian Federation]]<ref name=\"sakwa_p248\"/> and describes its ideology as \"New Socialism of the 21st century\", but emphasises that it does not wish to return to \"Soviet bureaucratic socialism\".{{citation needed|date=October 2018}} In the party platform, this \"New Socialism\" is defined as the antithesis of \"barbarous, oligarchic capitalism\". It represents a more [[individualism|individualist]] or [[liberal socialism]].<ref name=\"platform2\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20180727212226/http://www.sras.org/fair_and_just_russia_2 A Fair and Just Russia. The Political Platform of Russia's Social Democrats Part 2: The Individual & Government] The School of Russian and Asian Studies. Archived 27 July 2018.</ref><ref name=\"platform1\"/>\n\nImproving the socio-economic position of the average Russian is the party's primary aim. It wishes to replace Russia's 13% [[flat tax|flat income tax]] with [[progressive taxation]] and demands that spending on employment programmes is increased to 1% of GDP.<ref name=\"platform2\"/><ref name=\"platform1\"/> In the State Duma, the party emphasises its role as \"constructive opposition\" that opposes high-level corruption and supports further democratisation of the political system. In the [[5th State Duma|2007\u20132011 Duma]], A Just Russia declared absolute opposition to Prime Minister [[Vladimir Putin]]'s government, voting against the government's budgets in 2010 and 2011 while remaining strongly supportive of President [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and his [[Medvedev modernisation programme|modernisation programme]].<ref name=\"russia_analytical_digest_political_parties\"/>\n\n== Chairmen ==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!\u2116\n!Portrait\n!Chairmen\n!Took office\n!Left office\n|-\n!1\n|[[File:S M Mironov.jpg|90x90px|center]]\n|[[Sergey Mironov]]\n|28 October 2006\n|16 April 2011\n|-\n!2\n|[[File:Nikolay Levichev IF 09-2013 (1).jpg|90x90px|center]]\n|[[Nikolai Levichev]]\n|16 April 2011\n|27 October 2013\n|-\n!3\n|[[File:Sergey Mironov 2014-05-01 1.jpg|90x90px|center]]\n|[[Sergey Mironov]]\n|27 October 2013\n|Incumbent\n|}\n\n== International cooperation ==\nA Just Russia is a full member of the [[Socialist International]].\n\n== Electoral results ==\n=== Presidential elections ===\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Election year\n!rowspan=2|Candidate\n!colspan=2|1st round\n!colspan=2|2nd round\n|-\n!No. of overall votes\n!% of overall vote\n!No. of overall votes\n!% of overall vote\n|-\n![[2008 Rus